The Federal Ministry of Health has established a Ministerial Committee on health insurance provision for pensioners, the Executive Secretary of PTAD, Dr. Chioma Ejikeme, has said. She made this known yesterday at ongoing Southwest Stakeholders’ Forum, in Ibadan, Oyo State. She stated that with the establishment of the Ministerial Committee, pensioners under the old pension scheme, the Defined Benefits Scheme (DBS) would soon have access to health insurance.   FUTO, host communities’ 10-year-old land feud worsens     The farce this time     Abuja primary school teachers’ strike   Ejikeme, who said the Directorate prioritises welfare of pensioners, said PTAD and representatives of the Nigerian Union of Pensioners (NUP), are members of the committee. She said they are, in collaboration with some of our stakeholders, including the National Health Insurance Scheme, the National Senior Citizens Centre, and Federal Ministry of Health, to see how making health insurance available to pensioners could be a reality. She said the corona virus pandemic has led them to open more channels of communication and complaints resolution. She said despite the lockdown that occurred as a result of the  pandemic, PTAD continued to pay monthly pensions promptly, resolve complaints, cleare accrued arrears, paid death benefits to some next-of-kin and one-off payments of some defunct agencies.